  <h2>Font family example with a font stack</h2>
<code><pre>
<strong>CSS</strong>
p {
  color: blue;
  <strong>font-family: "Trebuchet MS", Verdana, sans-serif;</strong>
}</pre></code>
  <p>It is considered best practice to leave a generic font-type (e.g., sans-serif) at the end of the font stack in case the preceding fonts aren't available on one's device.</p>
  <h2>Font sizes</h2>
  <p>Remember, 1 <kbd><strong>em</strong></kbd> unit is equivalent to (at least when it comes to fonts) the font size set on the <strong>parent element</strong> of the current element. <kbd><strong>rem</strong></kbd> units are similar, but they apply to the <strong>root element</strong> set on the document rather than the selected element's parent element. In other words, their size is dependent on the font size given to the <kbd>&lt;html&gt;</kbd> element.</p>
  <p><strong>I already know a lot of the stuff covered in this section</strong>, but here's the <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Learn/CSS/Styling_text/Fundamentals">link to the MDN module</a> anyway in case I need to reference it. There's a bunch of helpful properties--like <kbd>font-stretch</kbd>--provided there that I wasn't in the mood to type out.</p>
